---
scope: src/service/docs/archive/
description: Archive every canonical page publish to Wayback Machine and emit an RSS/Atom feed entry as a durable append-only record.
intent: >
  On every canonical page publish — docs, agents, commands, and skills —
  guarantee that (a) a Wayback Machine Save Page Now snapshot exists and
  its URL is committed back to the build manifest so the next build can
  render it in the page header, and (b) an RSS/Atom feed entry has been
  written naming the change and linking to both the live and archived
  URLs. This makes every version of every canonical page citable from
  outside aidemd.dev itself, which is the forcing function behind the
  site's claim to be a durable canonical record. ActivityPub / Fediverse
  fan-out is deferred to v1.1.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - Every canonical page publish triggers a Wayback Save Page Now call; the resulting archive URL is stored in `build-manifest.json` committed back to the repo, and the next build reads the manifest and renders the archive URL in the page header.
    - "Every publish writes an RSS/Atom feed entry with a fixed template: aidemd.dev <type>: <file> updated. Source commit <sha>. Live: <url>. Archived: <wayback-url>. where <type> is one of docs, agents, commands, or skills."
    - Archive failures block the publish. Three retries on Wayback errors with exponential backoff; if retries exhaust, the publish aborts and the build reports the failure explicitly.
    - The RSS feed file at `/public/feed.xml` validates against the Atom or RSS 2.0 specification (required elements present, valid dates, stable GUIDs tied to versioned URLs).
    - The previous-version snapshot remains citable after a new version publishes; the manifest is append-only for published versions, and the feed entries are append-only.
  undesired:
    - Client-side archive logic. Wayback Save Page Now submission runs server-side at build time, never from a browser, and is never triggered by a page view. A page-view trigger is a spoofable tampering vector.
    - Marketing copy in feed entries. The RSS entries are legal artifacts, not a growth channel. No "Check out the new docs update!" prose, no "🚀" prefixes, no author bylines, no excerpts. The template is exact and unchanging.
    - Cron-based archival. Archiving runs coupled to the publish event, not on a schedule. A cron window means there exists a time when the live version is unarchived, which is exactly the evidentiary gap that breaks the priority claim.
    - Silent failure. Rate-limit errors must not be swallowed or logged-and-continued. They block the publish, the build reports them, and a human decides whether to retry, delay the publish, or flag a larger problem.
    - ActivityPub / Fediverse publishing in v1. The pattern is implementable but has no production precedent for canonical-docs sites (per research/aidemd-dev/canonical-record-publishing gaps). v1 ships RSS + Wayback only; ActivityPub moves to v1.1 with its own spec revision that names the outbox, signing keys, and recipient audience explicitly.
    - Wayback auth tokens or future Fediverse keys committed to the repo or exposed to client code. Secrets live in the build environment only.
    - In-place mutation of previously-published manifest entries or feed entries. Published versions are append-only; corrections are new entries with a link back to the corrected version.
---

## Context

Durable priority-date claims depend on third-party, timestamped,
tamper-resistant records existing for every live version of the
canonical source. Wayback Machine (run by the Internet Archive) and
RSS/Atom feeds (picked up by aggregators, consumed by feed readers,
archived by search engines) are the two such channels accessible to
a small team without legal infrastructure. If either channel is
missing for a specific version, that version's priority is weakened;
if archiving is decoupled from publishing (for example, via a cron
job), there exists a documented window where the live version is
unarchived and the argument "this page existed in this form on this
date" becomes rebuttable.

This submodule exists to make the publish step *atomic* with the
archive step: a publish is not complete until its snapshot has been
captured and its feed entry has been written. Everything else here
is downstream of that atomicity requirement.

This submodule narrows the parent (docs surface) to the specific
mechanical guarantee that every published version is durable outside
our own server. The docs surface talks about the site's role as a
record; this submodule talks about how that role survives the site
going down, being acquired, or being mutated.

## Strategy

**Archive runs as a publish step, not a background job.** The publish
sequence is: renderCanonical → post-render diff check → Wayback save
page now → RSS entry append → manifest commit → deploy. Each step
blocks the next on failure. If Wayback fails and retries exhaust,
the deploy does not run. If the feed file cannot be written, the
manifest is not committed. The publish is a transaction.

**Wayback submission uses the Save Page Now API.** On publish, the
service POSTs the new versioned URL to Wayback's save-page-now
endpoint, polls for completion, and records the resulting archive
URL. The archive URL is stored in `build-manifest.json` keyed by the
versioned URL, and the manifest is committed back to the repo as
part of the publish. The next build reads the manifest and renders
the archive URL in each page's DocHeader. This closes the loop:
every live page displays its own Wayback archive link.

**Retry with exponential backoff, then fail.** Three retries on
transient Wayback errors (rate limits, 5xx responses, timeouts),
with exponential backoff (e.g., 1s → 4s → 16s). On the fourth
failure, the publish aborts and the build reports "Wayback save
failed for <url> after 3 retries; publish blocked." No silent
degradation; the implementor must either retry manually or
investigate the root cause.

**RSS/Atom feed is written to `/public/feed.xml` at build time.**
The feed file is a templated write from the same `build-manifest.json`
that holds the Wayback archive URLs. Every entry contains: title (the
source file name), pub date (the publish commit timestamp), GUID (the
stable versioned URL, which is immutable and unique), live URL,
archive URL, and a one-line description following the fixed template.
The feed uses either Atom 1.0 or RSS 2.0 (implementor picks; both
are acceptable as long as the choice is consistent).

**Feed entry template is fixed and unchanging.** "aidemd.dev docs:
<file> updated. Source commit <sha>. Live: <url>. Archived:
<wayback-url>." No variation, no seasonal copy, no emoji, no author
name, no excerpt. The fixed template is the forcing function that
keeps the feed from drifting into marketing content — any proposal
to add a field to the entry requires a spec revision here.

**Append-only manifests and feeds.** When a new canonical version is
published, its entry is added to `build-manifest.json` and to
`feed.xml`; prior entries are never mutated, even to update URLs or
fix typos in descriptions. If a published snapshot needs a
correction, a new entry is appended linking back to the corrected
version. This mirrors the RFC/arXiv discipline: published artifacts
are frozen.

**Secrets live in the build environment.** Wayback auth (if required)
is read from environment variables injected into the build runner —
never committed to the repo, never passed to client code, never
logged. Future Fediverse signing keys will follow the same pattern.

**ActivityPub is a v1.1 spec revision, not a shortcut.** The
`publishActivityPub/` helper folder is reserved in the architect's
folder structure but is not implemented in v1. When v1.1 lands, it
gets its own outcome in a spec revision and its own helper submodule;
the v1 spec explicitly names its absence so the implementor does not
accidentally ship a half-built Fediverse publisher. v1 does not
import `activitypub-express`, does not scaffold an actor, does not
generate a signing key, does not create an outbox route.

**Quarterly re-verification is a v1.1 concern, not v1.** The
docs-surface spec names quarterly byte-faithfulness re-verification as
a tripwire; the mechanism for running that verification (comparing
live rendered pages against canonical sources months after publish)
is a separate audit service that does not live in this submodule and
is out of scope for v1. v1 ships publish-time archival; re-verification
is v1.1.

## Good examples

A canonical doc is updated at 14:03 UTC. The build runs; renderCanonical
produces the new HTML with a new content hash. The diff check passes.
The archive step calls Wayback Save Page Now at 14:03:47, polls for
the snapshot, and receives
`https://web.archive.org/web/20260411140352/aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec`.
The `build-manifest.json` is updated with a new entry:

```json
{
  "aide-spec@v20260411": {
    "live": "https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec@v20260411",
    "sourceCommit": "a1b2c3d",
    "publishedAt": "2026-04-11T14:03:00Z",
    "wayback": "https://web.archive.org/web/20260411140352/aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec"
  }
}
```

The RSS feed at `/public/feed.xml` gets a new entry:

```xml
<entry>
  <title>aide-spec.md</title>
  <id>https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec@v20260411</id>
  <published>2026-04-11T14:03:00Z</published>
  <link href="https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec@v20260411"/>
  <summary>aidemd.dev docs: aide-spec.md updated. Source commit a1b2c3d.
  Live: https://aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec@v20260411.
  Archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20260411140352/aidemd.dev/docs/aide-spec.</summary>
</entry>
```

The manifest is committed back to the repo as part of the publish. The
deploy runs. The page header at `/docs/aide-spec@v20260411` now displays
the archive URL alongside the publication date and commit SHA. Six
months later, a priority-date question is resolved in thirty seconds
by fetching the Wayback snapshot and pointing at the RSS entry
timestamp.

## Bad examples

Wayback submission is a client-side fetch that runs on every page
view, using an API key exposed in the browser bundle. Rate-limit errors
are swallowed with a `console.warn`, and the archive URL is never
stored; the docs pages display "Archived: pending…" indefinitely.

An RSS entry reads "🚀 Major update to AIDE docs — we've totally
refreshed the aide-spec! Check it out →" — indistinguishable from a
marketing feed, with no source commit and no Wayback URL. The feed's
legal-artifact value is gone.

The archive step fails due to a transient rate limit. The build logs
a warning "wayback failed, continuing anyway" and proceeds with the
deploy. An hour later, the docs are live but unarchived, and nobody
notices until a reader files a bug two weeks later — by which time
the "this page existed in this form on this date" argument has a
documented gap.

A cron job archives once every 24 hours, sweeping for any live pages
that were not yet archived. The cron window creates a documented
24-hour gap for every new publish — exactly the evidentiary gap the
spec says is forbidden.

A published manifest entry for `aide-spec@v20260328` is silently
mutated during a later build to update its `wayback` field to a new
snapshot URL after the old one broke. The entry is no longer a frozen
record; anyone who cited the old archive URL now links to a broken
page with no indication of what happened.

The v1 implementor scaffolds `publishActivityPub/` with a
"placeholder implementation" that generates a keypair, creates an
outbox route, and emits a dummy activity on every publish — none of
which is tested against a real Fediverse instance. The scaffold ships
and a security researcher finds the unprotected outbox three weeks
later. ActivityPub is explicitly out of v1; scaffolding it "for the
future" violates this spec.
